item.title: The Dutch have the best sports color
item.description: Orange is the historic national colour of the Netherlands, originating from one of the many title of the ruling head of state, Prince of Orange. The founder of the House of Orange, William the Silent, is like the Dutch George Washington. If George Washington had followed up his victory over the British by producing a whole line of Washington's with a fair number of them being military or political geniuses in their own right. Who repeatedly stood up, and at times gave their life, to save the nation at its most dire moments: Maurice of Orange (military genius), Frederick Henry of Orange (nicknamed 'the city breaker' for his skill at seiging), William III of Orange (successfully invaded and took over England), Wilhelmina Queen of the Netherlands (the icon of Dutch resistance against the Nazi occupation). And those are just the most illustrious, there's even more who weren't geniuses but did do their part in their time (and for the record, there were a few rotten apples too of course). Basically, unlike many of the European royal families which were often just imported from Germany when the native line died out coughenglandcough ;D, the House of Orange has been intimately tied with the history and fortunes of the Netherlands since our beginnings as an independent nation. https://old.reddit.com/r/olympics/comments/1y4e2l/why_do_we_always_see_the_dutch_in_the_color/cfhgj77/

item.title: Bride surprises wedding guests with stem cell donor who saved her life
item.description: Kaedi Cecala revealed the man whose selfless act gave her a second chance at life was among the wedding guests. A bride left wedding guests stunned and many in tears after revealing that the stem cell donor who saved her life was standing among them. Kaedi Cecala was diagnosed with myelodysplastic syndrome, a rare blood cancer, in 2020. After an aggressive chemotherapy regimen, doctors found a perfect match in Karol Zwierzyski, a 26-year-old living in Poland. The transplant was a success, and Kaedi is now cancer-free. At her wedding, Kaedi surprised guests by introducing Zwierzyski, who traveled from Poland to attend the celebration. Source: https://nationaltoday.com/us/il/chicago/news/2026/02/17/bride-surprises-wedding-guests-with-stem-cell-donor-who-saved-her-life/

item.title: Things seen this week during structural assessments!
item.description:
This is what happens when water intrusion goes unchecked and maintenance gets deferred. ? The entire framing system is saturated, rotted, and structurally compromised. When wood stays wet without airflow, it loses strength and begins to break down.
Hidden spall damage beneath a cantilevered pool area. ? Long-term moisture exposure reached the embedded steel reinforcement. As the steel corrodes and expands, it forces the surrounding concrete to crack and separate, eventually exposing the rebar. Spalling like this is a sign the structural element is deteriorating from the inside out.
Another structural Jenga for books! ☝️ This girder is being supported by stacked wood blocks that do not properly transfer structural loads and are not a safe long-term solution.
This picture was not taken at an angle. ? The post that is meant to hold this deck has shifted and is visibly leaning. When a support post moves, it no longer transfers loads straight down into the footing. That introduces bending stress, reduces its load-carrying capacity, and can lead to continued movement or failure.
When retaining walls are not properly engineered, pressure builds behind the wall and forces movement. One of the most common causes of hydrostatic pressure is a lack of drainage behind the wall. All of these plants require water, and that water needs somewhere to go.
The stem wall shows a vertical crack with visible efflorescence, indicating long-term moisture intrusion. ? Cracks like this typically form from settlement, soil movement, or hydrostatic pressure acting against the foundation. You can see that both sides of the crack are moving at different rates and separating from each other. This is called differential movement.
Without proper drainage, hydrostatic pressure builds behind the wall. Saturated soil increases lateral force, pushing the wall outward and widening existing cracks. Repairs typically involve improving drainage with proper backfill, perforated drain pipe, and weep systems. In more severe cases, the entire wall should be replaced.
These posts and piers are surrounded by expansive soil. Clay-rich soils expand when they absorb moisture and contract when they dry. That repeated swelling and shrinking puts pressure on posts and piers, causing them to move.
We went out to assess a hillside retaining wall that was showing signs of movement. What we found was a deteriorating footing caused by soil movement and long-term moisture exposure. We also found a Modelo bottle cast directly into the concrete. Honestly, we should start a weekly post showing the wild things we find on assessments. Oh wait… we already do. ?
